Question 1

pubmed %>%
  count(term, name = "number_abstracts")

  term            number_abstracts
  <chr>                      <int>

3 meningitis                   317
4 preeclampsia                 780
5 prostate cancer              787
token_counts <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>% #split the word of abstract into each word
  count(term, word, sort = TRUE) 

top5_tokens <- token_counts %>% 
  group_by(term) %>%  #split the word by term to see the top 5 words
  slice_max(n, n = 5)

top5_tokens %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder_within(word, n, term), y = n, fill = term)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ term, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_x_reordered() +
  labs(title = "Top 5 Most Common Tokens per Search Term",
        x = "Word",
       y = "Frequency")

There are 981 abstracts for COVID, 787 for prostate cancer, 780 for preeclampsia, 376 for cystic fibrosis, and 317 for meningitis. After splitting the abstracts into unigrams, we can see that for COVID, the top five most common words are âthe,â âof,â âcovid,â â19,â and âand.â For cystic fibrosis, the top five words are âthe,â âof,â âand,â âin,â and âto,â and for meningitis, they are âthe,â âof,â âand,â âin,â and âa.â Preeclampsia has âthe,â âof,â âand,â âin,â and âtoâ as the top five words, while prostate cancer has âthe,â âof,â âand,â âcancer,â and âprostate.â Interestingly, for every search term, âtheâ is the most common word. This makes sense because it is a stop word that people frequently use in writing. In fact, most of the top five words across all termsâsuch as âthe,â âand,â âof,â âin,â âto,â and âaââare stop words. I even used many of these stop words while answering this question, so it makes sense that they are the most commonly used words. For prostate cancer and COVID-19, aside from stop words, the disease names themselves also appear among the top five most common words.

After removing the stop words, we can see more meaningful insights from the data. For the single-word (unigram) analysis, COVID-related abstracts include terms such as âcovid,â â19,â âpatients,â âdisease,â and âpandemic,â which aligns with the nature of COVID-19 as a global health crisis. Cystic fibrosis has words âfibrosisâ, âcysticâ, âcfâ, âpatientsâ and âdiseaseâ. Meningitis has âpatientsâ, âmeningitisâ, âmeningealâ, âcsfâ, and âclinicalâ. Preeclampsia has âpreâ, âeclampsiaâ, âwomenâ and âpregnancyâ. Prostate cancer has âcancerâ, âprostateâ, âpatientsâ, âtreatmentâ, and âdiseaseâ.   coord_flip() +

    title = "Top 10 Most Common Bigrams per Term",

  )

Generally, we can see that the top 10 bigrams include combinations such as âcovid 19,â âof the,â âin the,â âprostate cancer,â âpatients with,â âof covid,â âand the,â and âto the.â Many of these bigrams consist of stop-word combinations or pairings of a stop word with a disease name. Overall, the top bigrams for each search term are primarily composed of disease names combined with stop words, or stop words paired together.

Question 4

word_counts <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  count(term, word, sort = TRUE)

tfidf <- word_counts %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, term, n) %>%  #Computes term frequency (TF) Ã inverse document frequency (IDF)
  arrange(desc(tf_idf))

top_tfidf <- tfidf %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(tf_idf, n = 5) %>%
  ungroup()

top_tfidf %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder_within(word, tf_idf, term), y = tf_idf, fill = term)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ term, scales = "free") +
  scale_x_reordered() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 5 TF-IDF Tokens per Search Term")

TFâIDF identifies words that are frequent within one topic but rare across others. Using the original dataset tokenized into single words, we can see that the top five tokens are now specific to each search term. For example, each termâs disease name appears as a distinctive token: âcovidâ is associated with the COVID term, and âcf,â âcystic,â or âfibrosisâ are associated with the cystic fibrosis term. More unique terms also emerge for each disease â for instance, âpregnancy,â âwomen,â and âhypertensionâ appear for preeclampsia, while âcftrâ and âairwayâ are for cystic fibrosis. In contrast, common stop words and general terms such as âpatientsâ and âdiseaseâ which dominated the frequency analyses in Questions 1 and 2, no longer appear here.

       y = "Proportion of Words", x = "Sentiment")

Some common sentiments identified are anger, anticipation, disgust, fear, joy, surprise, and trust. There are fewer instances of joy and surprise, which makes sense because people generally do not feel happy when they discover they are sick, and individuals usually seek clinical care when they feel unwell. Diseases like COVID-19 show both positive (trust) and negative emotions (fear and sadness). The positive tone is largely driven by trust, as people tend to rely on healthcare providers when facing a new or unknown disease. Chronic or treatable conditions such as prostate cancer and preeclampsia lean toward more positive or anticipatory tones. Meningitis has the least data overall and displays a relatively even mix of positive and negative sentiments.

Furthermore, we observe positive emotions for preeclampsia, possibly because it has a longer research history and is a more controllable and treatable condition. When we remove general polarity (positive or negative) and focus only on emotional tones, COVID-19, prostate cancer (to a lesser extent), and meningitis are dominated by fear, reflecting concern about uncertainty or disease severity. Preeclampsia shows anticipation, likely due to the abundance of literature and clinical studies exploring this condition. Cystic fibrosis shows disgust, which may be associated with the nature of its symptoms.

Question 6

pubmed <- pubmed %>%
  mutate(id = row_number())   # gives each abstract a unique numeric ID

afinn <- get_sentiments("afinn")

afinn_sent <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  inner_join(afinn, by = "word") %>%
  group_by(term, id) %>%             
  summarise(mean_score = mean(value), .groups = "drop")  

afinn_sent %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = term, y = mean_score, fill = term)) +
  geom_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE, alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of AFINN Sentiment Scores by Search Term",
    x = "Search Term",
    y = "Average Positivity Score (per Abstract)"
  )

AFINN is a sentiment analysis tool that uses a predefined list of words, or âlexicon,â with associated polarity scores ranging from â5 (most negative) to +5 (most positive). The medians appear similar across search terms and cluster around zeroâespecially for meningitis, preeclampsia, and prostate cancerâindicating a generally balanced tone. COVID-19 abstracts show slightly negative median scores, likely due to discussions of risk, death, or disease. In contrast, cystic fibrosis exhibits a slightly more positive median and a wider interquartile range, suggesting a more positive overall sentiment.
